{"title_page": "Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria", "text_new": "{{for|the Christian image in the Philippines|Our Lady of Guidance}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria\n| native_name                     = \n| other_name                      = \n| translit_lang1_type             = Spanish\n| translit_lang1_info             = Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria\n| settlement_type                 = [[Municipalities of Spain|Municipality]]\n| image_skyline                   = Vista de atalaya.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = View of La Atalaya\n| image_size                      = \n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_alt                        = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_alt                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = Gran Canaria municipio Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria.svg\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Municipal location in Gran Canaria\n| pushpin_map                     = Spain Province of Las Palmas#Canary Islands#Spain with Canary Islands\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in the province of Las Palmas\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|28|8|20|N|15|37|58|W|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[Spain]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Autonomous Community]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Canary Islands]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Provinces of Spain|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Province of Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Island\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Gran Canaria]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| leader_party                    = [[Nueva Canarias]]\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Pedro Manuel Rodr\u00edguez P\u00e9rez\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=area>[http://www.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/jaxi-istac/menu.do?uripub=urn:uuid:fbc0bdc8-cacb-43b8-a5cb-a93f745dcff6 Instituto Canario de Estad\u00edstica], area</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 42.59\n| elevation_footnotes             = ([[AMSL]])\n| elevation_m                     = 180\n| population_as_of                = {{Spain metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_footnotes            = {{Spain metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n| population_total                = {{Spain metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| timezone1                       = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +0\n| timezone1_DST                   = CEST (GMT +1)\n| utc_offset1_DST                 = +1\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 35450\n| area_code                       = [[+34]] (Spain) + 928 (Las Palmas)\n| twin1                           = \n| twin1_country                   = \n| website                         = [http://www.santamariadeguia.es/joomla/santamariadeguia/ www.santamariadeguia.es]\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria''' is a town and a municipality in [[Las Palmas (province)|Las Palmas]] province of the [[Canary Islands]]. It is located on the north side of [[Gran Canaria]] island. Its population is {{formatnum:13811}} (2013),<ref name=pop>[http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas/E30260A_1/php/pob_001.php?anyo=2013&territorio=35023 Instituto Canario de Estad\u00edstica], population</ref> and the area is {{convert|42.59|km\u00b2|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=area/>\n\nThe town Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda is situated in a valley {{convert|2|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from the coast, {{convert|19|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} west of [[Las Palmas]]. The municipality stretches from the coast into the mountainous interior of the island. The [[Autopista GC-2|GC-2 motorway]] passes north of the town.\n\n== Toponimy ==\nCurrently the municipality takes its name from its municipal capital, combined the invocation of its primitive hermitage founded in honor of [[Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda]] at the end of the fifteenth century.<ref> {{cite book | last= L\u00f3pez Garc\u00eda| first= J.S| title = Origin and development of the historical centers of the Region of Ag\u00e1ldar: G\u00e1ldar and Gu\u00eda | url= https://mdc.ulpgc.es/cdm/ref/collection/coloquios/id/1854 | year = 1984 | others = Coordinated by Francisco Morales Padr\u00f3n | publisher = [[Cabildo insular|Cabildo]] de [[Gran Canaria]] | location = [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] | isbn = 84-85628-57-8}} </ref>\n\nDuring the [[Guanches|aboriginal stage]] of the island, which ends in the year 1483, the population nucleus received the denomination of ''Agu\u00eda'', corresponding to the existing population in the same location of the historical center and surroundings, and also near the aboriginal from ''[[Agaldar]]'', capital of a [[guanarteme]] chiefdom. This denomination was maintained until 1555, as indicated in the land and water distribution documents of Gran Canaria, granted after the European conquest of the island.\n\nAfter the [[Conquest of the Canary Islands|European conquest]], the historical nucleus was named as ''Villa de Gu\u00eda'', simplifying as ''Gu\u00eda'', and it remained that way throughout the [[Colonial era|colonial period]], until the 19th century. Already in the 19th century begins to predominate the denomination of ''Guia de Gran Canaria'', within a stream of administrative modernization and especially to differentiate it from other homonymous populations such as [[Gu\u00eda de Isora]], on the island of [[Tenerife]].<ref> {{cite book | last = Madoz | first = Pascual | title = Geographic-statistical-historical dictionary of Spain and its possessions of Overseas | url= http://www.bibliotecavirtualdeandalucia.es/catalogo/consulta/registro.cmd?id=6353 | volume = IX | year = 1847 | publisher = Est. Universal typographic-literary | location = [[Madrid]] | page = 77}}</ref><ref> {{cite book | last = Viera and Clavijo | first = Jos\u00e9 de | title = News of the general history of the Canary Islands | url =https://www.laprovincia.es/opinion/2008/03/18/recuperar-denominacion-guia-gran-canaria/137767.html |year=1950\u20131952 |orig-year=1772 |editor= El\u00edas Serra Rafols |publisher=Goya Editions |location=[[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]]}}</ref><ref> {{cite news | first = Pedro | last = Gonz\u00e1lez-Sosa | title = Retrieve the denomination Gu\u00eda of Gran Canaria | url =http://mdc.ulpgc.es/cdm/compoundobject/collection/MDC/id/162635/rec/49 | newspaper = La Provincia. Diario de Las Palmas | publisher = [[La Provincia|Prensa Ib\u00e9rica]] |date = March 17, 2008 |access-date = November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref> {{cite web |last = Aguiar Castellano |first=Sergio |year = 2008 |title = Regarding the name change of the municipality of GU\u00cdA | publisher=Ciudaddeguia.com |location= \u00a1Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria |issn = | url=http://www.guiadegrancanaria.org/documentacion/sergio_aguiar/saguiar_cambiar-nombre-municipio_pdf.pdf  | access-date = November 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlready in the twentieth century and within the period of the [[Franco dictatorship]], on December 28, 1962, the mayor of that time, Rafael Vel\u00e1zquez Garc\u00eda, proposed to change the official name to that of ''Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda'', incorporating the invocation of the Catholic religious temple existing in the municipality since the 16th century. The change was approved in full by the local corporation on April 26, 1963, subsequently obtaining the approval of the [[Cabildo insular|Island Council]] de [[Gran Canaria]], which had been denied in the first instance, the change being to ''Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria'' by agreement of the Council of Ministers of the Franco government on July 23, 1963. <ref> {{cite web | url =http://www.descubreguia.com/contenidos/70-Historia.html | title = History | access-date = November 15, 2018}} </ref> <ref> {{cite book | title = Today, patron feast of Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda | url =https://jable.ulpgc.es/jable/el.eco.de.canarias/1965/08/15/0005.htm?palabras=guia+gran+canaria | newspaper = El Eco de Canarias | date = 15 August 1965 | access-date = November 15, 2018}} </ref>\n\nIn 2008, the City Council promoted a debate from the municipal website for neighbors to express their opinion on whether or not to officially retake the name of ''Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria''. <ref> {{cite news | first = M. J. | last = Monz\u00f3n | title = A name to debate | url= https://www.laprovincia.es/gran-canaria/2008/05/26/nombre-debate/153382.html | newspaper = [[La Provincia]]. Diario de Las Palmas | publisher = Prensa Ib\u00e9rica | date = May 26, 2008 | access-date = November 15, 2018}} </ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File: Vista de atalaya.jpg|thumb|250px|left| View of The Watchtower of Sta. M\u00aa de Gu\u00eda.]]\nLocated in the north of Gran Canaria, the municipality has a triangular shape, which places its [[Vertex (geometry) | vertex]] towards the south, near the [[Volcanic caldera | caldera]] of the Pinos de [[ G\u00e1ldar]]. To the east it borders the municipality of [[Moya, Las Palmas|Moya]] defined by [[Barranco de Moya]] until its mouth. To the west, the division follows some channels, surrounds the Pico de La Atalaya or G\u00e1ldar mountain, and continues to the coast, dividing the Pico de la Atalaya in two.\n\nThe coastline is defined between [[Caleta de Arriba]] until the mouth of the Barranco de Moya. The coasts are rocky due to erosion, cliffs predominate, although with exceptions such as San Felipe beach, which in summer is covered with sand.\n\n=== Climatology ===\nThe climatic conditions of Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda derive from its northern position. Thus, there are three altitudinal steps, which are:\n\n* The coastal zone, which reaches up to 300 meters;\n* The medians between 300 and 600 meters;\n* The high zone, from 600 meters.\n\nAs it enters the interior of the island the number of sunny days per year is less; It rains more and temperatures are generally lower.\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=center\n|cols=2\n| 1991 | 12383 \n| 1996 | 13117 \n| 2001 | 13893 \n| 2002 | 14171 \n| 2003 | 14255\n| 2004 | 14107 \n| 2013 | 13811\n}}\n\n==Heritage sites==\n\nThe [[caves of Valer\u00f3n]], also called ''cenobio de Valer\u00f3n'', is a [[property of cultural interest]] in the \"archaeological site\" category. It is the largest pre-Hispanic collective granary. Its size is representative of Gran Canaria agriculture, unique among the Canaries islands in that it was traditionally dominated by plantations, with much of these being grains, rather than by stock-breeding.<ref name=\"arqu\">[http://www.arqueologiacanaria.com/Arqueologia_Canaria/Cenobio_de_Valeron.html Cenobio de Valeron], section \"''El yacimiento arqueologico''\". On ''arqueologiacanaria.com''.</ref>\n\nThe [[Casa Quintana|Quintana House]] is a sample of the ancient architecture of the municipality of Guia de Gran Canaria in the Canarian island of Gran Canaria, located in the Plaza Mayor de Gu\u00eda and its buildings date from the [[16th century]]. The Canarian balcony is of [[Mud\u00e9jar art|Mudejar style]], in wood and coat of arms with the surnames Guanarteme and Quintana.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of municipalities in Las Palmas]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mancomunidaddelnorte.org/guia.htm mancomunidaddelnorte.org]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria\n|North     = ''[[Atlantic Ocean]]''\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Moya, Las Palmas|Moya]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = \n|Southwest = G\u00e1ldar\n|West      = [[G\u00e1ldar, Las Palmas|G\u00e1ldar]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Municipalities in Las Palmas|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Gran Canaria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santa Maria de Guia de Gran Canaria}}\n[[Category:Municipalities in Gran Canaria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria\n| native_name                     = \n| other_name                      = \n| translit_lang1_type             = Spanish\n| translit_lang1_info             = Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria\n| settlement_type                 = [[Municipalities of Spain|Municipality]]\n| image_skyline                   = Vista de atalaya.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = View of La Atalaya\n| image_size                      = \n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_alt                        = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_alt                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = Gran Canaria municipio Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria.svg\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Municipal location in Gran Canaria\n| pushpin_map                     = Spain Province of Las Palmas#Canary Islands#Spain with Canary Islands\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in the province of Las Palmas\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|28|8|20|N|15|37|58|W|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| c