{"title_page": "World of Oz", "text_new": "{{short description|English psychedelic pop band in the 1960s}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = The World of Oz\n| image = Fenklup1968WorldofOz.jpg\n| caption = World of Oz (Dutch TV, May 1968)\n| origin = Birmingham west midlands, England\n| background = group_or_band\n| genre = {{flatlist |\n* [[Psychedelic pop]] \n* [[psychedelic rock]]\n}}\n| label = [[Deram Records|Deram]]\n| years_active = 1968 - 1969\n}}\n\nThe '''World of Oz''' was an English [[psychedelic pop]] band who released a sole [[eponymous|self-titled]] [[Gramophone record|LP]] in 1968, before fading into relative obscurity, although [[Compact Disc|CD]] re-issues of the album are now widely available to the public. \n\nThe band formed in January 1968 and signed to [[Deram Records]] on 13 February 1968. Their song, \"The Muffin Man\", was a minor hit in the UK and [[United States|US]] and reached the Top 10 in a number of [[Europe]]an countries, including the [[Netherlands]] and [[Belgium]]. Publicity for the single in the US was constrained because the marketing budget was limited. The reason being, manager [[Barry Class]] left the band to manage his other band, [[The Foundations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://badcatrecords.com/BadCat/WORLDofOZ.htm|title=B|work=badcatrecords.com}}</ref>\n\nDespite the lack of a hit US single, the band recorded their only album with changing lineups. They broke up soon after its release in 1969.<ref>allmusic [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p42468/biography|pure_url=yes}} The World of Oz biography]</ref>\n\nThey appeared on the [[BBC2]] television program, \"[[Colour Me Pop]]\" on 8 March 1969. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.marmalade-skies.co.uk/world_of_oz.htm|title = World of Oz|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2015|website = Marmalade Skies|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Also in 1969, they were one of the musical acts (alongside Karlheinz Stockhousen, Tristram Carey, Daphne Oram and others) featured in David Buckton's BBC television documentary on electronic music production, \"The Same Trade As Mozart\", in the \"Workshop\" series (programme number LMA7125P). Their appearance concerned the multi-track techniques used in one of their recording sessions. This contribution is unacknowledged in the programme's catalogue entry.\n\n== Line-up ==\n* Christopher Robin Evans ([[vocals]]/[[guitar]])\n* Tony Clarkson ([[Bass guitar|bass]])\n* David 'Kube' Kubinec (guitar/[[Organ (music)|organ]])\n* David Reay ([[drums]])\n* [[Geoff Nicholls]] (organ)\n* Rob Moore (drums)\n<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\t\n* ''The World of Oz'' (March 1969)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"The Muffin Man\" b/w \"Peter's Birthday\" (May 1968)\n* \"King Croesus\" b/w \"Jack\" (August 1968)\n* \"Willow's Harp\" b/w \"Like a Tear\" (February 1969)\n* \"The Hum Gum Tree\" b/w \"Beside The Fire\" (1969-unissued)\n(all of the above singles tracks except for \"Peter's Birthday\" was from their LP)\n<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.discogs.com/artist/291186-World-Of-Oz-The|title = World Of Oz, The|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2015|website = Discogs|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marmalade-skies.co.uk/world_of_oz.htm The World of Oz at Marmalade Skies]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=80oTELgl-Mc The Muffin Man video]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World of Oz}}\n[[Category:British pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Deram Records artists]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1969]]\n\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English psychedelic pop band in the 1960s}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = The World of Oz\n| image = Fenklup1968WorldofOz.jpg\n| caption = World of Oz (Dutch TV, May 1968)\n| origin = Birmingham west midlands, England\n| background = group_or_band\n| genre = {{flatlist |\n* [[Psychedelic pop]] \n* [[psychedelic rock]]\n}}\n| label = [[Deram Records|Deram]]\n| years_active = 1968 - 1969\n}}\n\nThe '''World of Oz''' was an English [[psychedelic pop]] band who released a sole [[eponymous|self-titled]] [[Gramophone record|LP]] in 1968, before fading into relative obscurity, although [[Compact Disc|CD]] re-issues of the album are now widely available to the public. \n\nThe band formed in January 1968 and signed to [[Deram Records]] on 13 February 1968. Their song, \"The Muffin Man\", was a minor hit in the UK and [[United States|US]] and reached the Top 10 in a number of [[Europe]]an countries, including the [[Netherlands]] and [[Belgium]]. Publicity for the single in the US was constrained because the marketing budget was limited. The reason being, manager [[Barry Class]] left the band to manage his other band, [[The Foundations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://badcatrecords.com/BadCat/WORLDofOZ.htm|title=B|work=badcatrecords.com}}</ref>\n\nDespite the lack of a hit US single, the band recorded their only album with changing lineups. They broke up soon after its release in 1969.<ref>allmusic [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p42468/biography|pure_url=yes}} The World of Oz biography]</ref>\n\nThey appeared on the [[BBC2]] television program, \"[[Colour Me Pop]]\" on 8 March 1969. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.marmalade-skies.co.uk/world_of_oz.htm|title = World of Oz|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2015|website = Marmalade Skies|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Also in 1969, they were one of the musical acts (alongside Karlheinz Stockhousen, Tristram Carey, Daphne Oram and others) featured in David Buckton's BBC television documentary on electronic music production, \"The Same Trade As Mozart\", in the \"Workshop\" series (programme number LMA7125P). Their appearance concerned the multi-track techniques used in one of their recording sessions. This contribution is unacknowledged in the programme's catalogue entry.\n\n== Line-up ==\n* Christopher Robin Evans ([[vocals]]/[[guitar]])\n* Tony Clarkson ([[Bass guitar|bass]])\n* David 'Kube' Kubinec (guitar/[[Organ (music)|organ]])\n* David Reay ([[drums]])\n* Geoff Nicholls (organ)\n* Rob Moore (drums)\n<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\t\n* ''The World of Oz'' (March 1969)\n\n===Singles===\n* \"The Muffin Man\" b/w \"Peter's Birthday\" (May 1968)\n* \"King Croesus\" b/w \"Jack\" (August 1968)\n* \"Willow's Harp\" b/w \"Like a Tear\" (February 1969)\n* \"The Hum Gum Tree\" b/w \"Beside The Fire\" (1969-unissued)\n(all of the above singles tracks except for \"Peter's Birthday\" was from their LP)\n<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.discogs.com/artist/291186-World-Of-Oz-The|title = World Of Oz, The|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2015|website = Discogs|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marmalade-skies.co.uk/world_of_oz.htm The World of Oz at Marmalade Skies]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=80oTELgl-Mc The Muffin Man video]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World of Oz}}\n[[Category:British pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Deram Records artists]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1969]]\n\n\n{{UK-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nectar3", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_of_Oz"}
{"title_page": "Katharine Preston", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n'''Katherine Preston''' is a British writer and public speaker. Her work has appeared in a number of publications, including the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[Psychology Today]]'', and ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Preston|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/katherine-preston|website=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=20 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nPreston graduated with a degree in History from [[Durham University]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hatfield College : Alumni|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/hatfield.college/alumni/|website=Durham University|accessdate=20 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> She worked in [[asset management]] before moving to America to write a memoir on her experiences as a [[stuttering|stutterer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Preston|url=https://www.investopedia.com/contributors/502/|website=[[Investopedia]]|language=en}}</ref> The book, ''Out With It: How Stuttering Helped Me Find My Voice'', was published by [[Simon & Schuster]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Preston|url=http://www.simonandschuster.co.uk/authors/Katherine-Preston/402143070|website=Simon & Schuster|accessdate=20 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Preston, Katherine}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women writers]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hatfield College, Durham]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n'''Katherine Preston''' is a British writer and public speaker. Her work has appeared in a number of publications, including the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', ''[[Psychology Today]]'', and ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Preston|url=https